instruction: [INST] Analyze this file to learn MacBook motherboard repair. The 'definitions' section explains key technical terms. The 'threads' section contains real-world repair discussions. Use both sections to understand and learn how to troubleshoot MacBook issues. Posts from username 'larossmann' , 'dukefawks' , and '2informaticos' are posts from trusted experts.[/INST]

definitions.A2141: What is A2141? A2141 is a model number for a 16 inch size MacBook Pro Retina from years 2019 with EMC 3347, that may contain one of these boards depending on the year & configuration: 820-01700..
definitions.820-01700: What is 820-01700? a LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER.
definitions.PPBUS_G3H: What is PPBUS_G3H? Main system power rail that charges the battery, or is power from the battery, that everything else is powered from. .
definitions.PP1V8_SLPS2R: What is PP1V8_SLPS2R? PP1V8_SLPS2R is a 1.8v power rail present when the system is in a SLPS2R state. .
definitions.U7000: What is U7000? U7000 refers to the ISL6258 or ISL6259 charging IC on Macbooks from 2008-2012.
definitions.3V3_G3H_RTC: What is 3V3_G3H_RTC? 3V3_G3H_RTC Is an abbreviation of PP3V3_G3H_RTC which is one of the first rails that has to come on in order for the USB-C mux chip to be powered in the T2 chip Macbook Pros..

"<SIGNAL>PPBUS_G3H</SIGNAL> to ground: 17.7 Ohms"
Did you test with charger, or battery connected???

I suspect angle sensors issue.

threads.title: Macbook Pro <MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER>A2141</MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER> <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-01700</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-05 Wont turn on.
threads.message:
Don't write end "V" after diode mode reading.
We don't want to make confusion with voltage measurment.
I hope you've got 0.003 witout charger connected.
For low values (under 0.005), switch to ohm mode.

You can try first injecting voltage.
There are many components connected, not only <CHIP>U7800</CHIP>.
Is not pure short, but an IR cam may help you to find the culprit.
Remove CPU/GPU heatsink first.
Then start injecting 1V; you can slowly increase until 2V (no more).
Set the amp limit to max first, on the lab PSU.

STOP checking in ohm scale.
Switch from diode mode to ohm scale ONLY for very low values; usually under 0.005-0.010 in diode mode.

6 or 15 ohm there is bad anyway.
You should get 0.300-0.450 in diode mode; depends of the multimeter used.
